<div type="translation" source="bib:Gillet2024_01">

<p>If we put the two fragments <supplied reason="explanation">#65 &amp; #66</supplied> together we have the following text, for which I propose a tentative translation <supplied reason="explanation">it may refer to a donation of goat for a lamp for someone who died</supplied>:</p><p>{nothing} ‡ <supplied reason="explanation">1</supplied> ṭaiyārkku ˚ippaḻuvūr ˚irukkum</p><p><supplied reason="explanation">1</supplied> {unlegible} ‡ <supplied reason="explanation">2</supplied> maṉṟāṭi ˚aṇitiraṉ colai ˚a</p><p><supplied reason="explanation">2</supplied> yāṉ muttaṉ <supplied reason="subaudible">korai</supplied> cirāḷḷai paṭa X ‡ <supplied reason="explanation">3</supplied> kola koṉṟa muttaṉai kāri</p><p><supplied reason="explanation">3</supplied> ṭṭamāṭṭātu ˚avaṉ taṅkaḷ nā<supplied reason="subaudible">lu</supplied> X X ‡ <supplied reason="explanation">4</supplied> ˚aṇitiraṉ colai korai cirāḷ</p><p><supplied reason="explanation">4</supplied> X <supplied reason="subaudible">ṉ</supplied>c cātti ˚avaṉukku ˚āka ˚aṇitiraṉ colai X ‡ <supplied reason="explanation">5</supplied> tevarkku cantirātittavaṟ ˚iravum</p><p><supplied reason="explanation">5</supplied> X lum ˚eriya vaitta nontāviḷakku ˚oṉ<supplied reason="subaudible">ṟu</supplied> ‡ <supplied reason="explanation">6</supplied> vaitta cāvāmūvāp perāṭu</p><p><supplied reason="explanation">6</supplied> X ṇūṟu toṇṇūṟum ˚ivai paṉmā X ‡ <supplied reason="explanation">7</supplied> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <foreign>śva</foreign>ra ra<foreign>kṣai</foreign> ||</p><p><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> for the Lord <supplied reason="explanation"><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/><foreign>ṭaiyārkku</foreign></supplied> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> the shepherd <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>maṉṟāṭi</foreign></supplied> Aṇitiraṉ Cōlai Muttaṉ Korai Cirāḷḷai <supplied reason="explanation">?</supplied> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> who resides <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>irukkum</foreign></supplied> in this Paḻuvūr <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> was killed <supplied reason="explanation">? <foreign>paṭa</foreign><supplied reason="lost"><foreign>k</foreign></supplied><foreign>ola koṉṟa</foreign></supplied> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> Aṇitiraṉ Cōlai <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> to him <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>avaṉukku</foreign></supplied>, on behalf of <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>cātti</foreign></supplied> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> to the god <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>tēvarkku</foreign></supplied>, as long as the sun and the moon endure, night <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>iravum</foreign></supplied> and day <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>pakalum</foreign></supplied>, gave <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>vaitta</foreign></supplied> to burn <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>eriya</foreign></supplied>; he gave <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>vaitta</foreign></supplied> for one perpetual lamp <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>nontāviḷakku oṉṟu</foreign></supplied> ninety <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>toṇṇūṟum</foreign></supplied> undying and non-ageing <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>cāvāmūvā</foreign></supplied> great goats <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>perāṭu</foreign></supplied>. They <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>ivai</foreign></supplied> are under the protection of the Paṉmāheśvaras.</p></div>

